  "prompt": "Was Hillary Clinton reading her speech from a paper in the third debate?",
  "response": "As of my knowledge cutoff in October 2023, there is no credible evidence or widely reported information suggesting that Hillary Clinton was reading her speech from a paper during the third presidential debate. In presidential debates, it's common for candidates to have notes or key points to reference; however, debates are generally designed to allow for spontaneous dialogue and responses rather than the reading of prepared speeches verbatim.\n\nDuring the 2016 third presidential debate between Hillary Clinton and Donald Trump, both candidates were observed engaging directly with each other's points and questions from moderators. While Clinton, like many politicians, may have had notes to help guide her responses, there were no notable reports or observations indicating that she was reading her remarks from a script or paper in a manner that significantly deviated from typical debate practices.\n\nIf you're referring to a different debate or a specific incident, please provide more details, and I can offer a more targeted response based on the information available up to October 2023.",
